  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Sensory function is different in persistent postherniotomy pain patients than in operated
      controls, suggesting this to be a neuropathic pain syndrome. By performing quantitative
      sensory testing, the specific changes in pain patients will be revealed, thereby aiding in
      designing future treatment trials. MRI scans of the groin regions in pain patients and
      control patients will be evaluated by senior MRI specialists assessing potential pathology to
      the region (Mesh, inflammation, edema, funicle etc.) Assessors will be blinded to clinical
      status, and surgery.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
